<font color="#FF0000">CIVILIANS AND WATER BUFFALOS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Sep  2  0:40:03 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
This thread reminds me of the time, we were medivaced to DaNang 1st med hospital. After weeks of combat, what did everyone decide to see on TV? <br>
 COMBAT.<br>
Now that those civilians are out of the way, it always happened that way, just when you got Clear Fields of Fire, they crossed your path.<br>
Water buffalos were just as stubborn, and just as stupid. <br>
March 1, 1968<br>
On the first day of March, we finally went out as a reactionary force and suffered no causalities nor did we engage the enemy. We had humped for about six clicks but had made no contact with the enemy. The area was scattered with war debris, numerous large craters pockmarked the area and only one or two huts remained in the many villages we came across. By late that afternoon we hadn't seen another living soul in the area. The area had been cleared months after operation Foster there had been Citrus and the Arizona area had been cleared of civilians, animals and the rice it produced.<br>
.<br>
&quot;Aggie, is this a free-fire zone?&quot; I asked. <br>
&quot;Yeah! anything moving, is fair game.&quot; Aggie hadn't forgotten the gooks that he had surprised in this area not too long ago when we had set up at the old French fort.<br>
&quot;Aggie, is that water buffalo out there a VC water buffalo or is he a friendly?&quot; <br>
&quot;If he's here and moving he's VC.  That water buffalo is VC, he bawled us when we came up.&quot; <br>
By now two other Marines were pointing their M16's at the water buffalo. As soon as Aggie said that the water buffalo was a confirmed VC they opened up with three or four rounds each. The large animal just stood still looking at us.  He had at least six bullet holes in him and hadn't budged a bit. One of the Marines opened up with two more bullets. The thud they made as they went into the hard water buffalo's skin and the damage they were doing didn't seem to phase the beast. <br>
&quot;Shot him in the back you have to break his spine to bring them down,&quot; Welsh said. <br>
Three more bullets were fired at the water buffalo and he bend his two front legs a little. Three more rounds and he sat down. I opened up with six rounds from the M60 machine gun and the beast fell head first into the mud. He twisted and turned and went down on his side. He tried to get up then turned to face us, bawled loudly then stopped moving. Chino in 2nd squad carried the M79, he fired a grenade into the beast and a chunk of meat flew off in several directions. The water buffalo feet went straight up in the air, he kicked out and stopped moving. Another water buffalo about 20 yards away upon hearing the grenades explosion bellowed and high stepped into the thick bamboo. <br>
&quot;Well, that VC got away,&quot; Aggie said.<br>
 On 5th of March, Mike company came in to men our lines. 3rd platoon was sent to men the lines at battalion headquarters and we prepared to go out on another operation, Operation Rock, an operation many of us would not come back from, an operation many of us would remember.<br>
